  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-accepted-adversarial",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team accepted the simulation evidence on the basis that NIH predictions agreed with mock-loop measurements within 18% across all five steady-state operating points and that Monte Carlo UQ was performed. The team noted the steady-state validation regime but concluded that the agreement was sufficient to support the pulsatile VAD claim by analogy. This reasoning constitutes the D3 undercutting defeater: the inference from steady-state validation agreement to pulsatile COU credibility is not structurally supported, because the hemolysis damage accumulation mechanism differs qualitatively between regimes. The primary validation result object (no-comparator) additionally lacks a comparedAgainst link, leaving the comparator identity unresolvable by automated SHACL checks, triggering W-AR-05. The Accepted outcome is the adversarial flaw — a correctly conducted assessment would return Not Accepted pending pulsatile validation data.",
